Pardon me if I am mistaken, but does anyone else notice a similarity here between this and Varulv's post? Ah, is this a continuation which I have stumbled into?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> &quot;You may not steal kills.<br>
Kill Stealing is defined as the killing of an NPC for any reason that is already fighting or pursuing another player or group without that group's specific permissio.<br>
<br>
The intent of this rule is discourage and make note of habitual Kill Stealers, not to punish those who honestly try to work together or those who make an honest mistake. Its enforcement by the EverQuest Customer Service Staff will reflect this philosophy<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
From a post by Ytrok. I cannot be bothered to read that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> whole</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> thread again, but I am of the firm belief that you should play by the rules as well as the spirit. Obviously, I am in a minority of one here :P<br>
<br>
The mob is irrelevant: Lodizal or an orc pawn. If it has been previously engaged, then Verant has <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> explicitly</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> stated that the mob belongs to the individual or group which engaged the mob first. <br>
<br>
I am unsure which person stated the opinion that if you have a problem with that, then simply wait for that person to either (i) kill the mob - unlikely, if not impossible with Lodizal if it does summon? or (ii) for that person to die <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> then</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> kill the mob.<br>
<br>
Yes, option (ii) may go against the spirit of the rules but I may be a little miffed, but could hardly object if someone or a group took this approach. Obviously, it is a hard-assed, arsey way to play, but equitable and fair in a situation as described. Rather that than simply steal a mob which has been previously engaged. Whether the individual or group <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> could</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> kill the mob is irrelevant. Wait for them to die. Hard-assed and arsey, but hey! at least no accusations of kill-stealing. <br>
<br>
Being a bastard is no biggie, and if option (ii) would render one a bastard than I must conclude that I am a wannabe bastard by my own words.<br>
<br>
As explained in the previous thread, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> consistency</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is king: You cannot use the rules to defend your position when it is convenient. Either abide by the rules or freely admit to tip-toeing over them.<br>
<br>
I may know <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> nada</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, absolutely nothing about the high-end game, but I don't think I particularly wish to be involved in that aspect if this thread is the result.<br>
<br>
Oh, if this 'Honor and Respect' Part 2 excuse my intrusion and carry on as normal.<br>
